This flips the likelihoods from my previous forecast that I didn't resile from immediately. I found 7 CON leadership contests between 1989 and 2013. They had durations:   1. 1989, 12 days;
  2. 1990, 13 days;
  3. 1995, 12 days;
  4. 1997, 48 days;
  5. 2001, 66 days;
  6. 2003, 14 days;
  7. 2016, 19 days. This gives a mean of ~26.29 days. Taking the *assumption* that these are exponentially distributed because time can never be less than 0, and there are some heavy-tailed items there. Kolmogorv-Smirnov can't rule it out (p~0.29). Taken together, Pr[Replace <= 36 days] ~= 0.75. these give a likelihood value of 75%: > quantile(rexp(1000000, rate=1/26.28571), c(0.74, 0.75, 0.76))      74%      75%      76%
35.46428 36.48969 37.57957 I am *choosing* to ignore my previous estimates because they were Pr[Replacement <= 2019-07-01 | {factors}]. Those factors, such as a resignation, have come to pass, so their probability should (incoherently) be given a value of 1. It's easier to just drop them and take a direct shot at it.   I'm leaving 1% in LAB and other because I can't give fractions of a percent and I can't give 0% as a probability. Notes: t.test mean 95% CI: [6.17, 46.40], sample mean = 26.29, sample sd = 21.75, Median is between 12 and 48. References, mostly pages like https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/YYYY_Conservative_Party_(UK)_leadership_election -- though I changed the year for each one. I stumbled on each plausible year by looking over http://www.election.demon.co.uk/conleader.html. Finally, where Wiki didn't have the start date for a contest I looked over BBC articles for an indication of "start", e.g. when a leader resigned or a challenger declared themselves. An initial estimate based on the normal distribution (ha!) gave 71/29 likelihoods, which is surprisingly close.

Revising "yes, Conservative" down from 12%. Technicals;
• Theresa May can't be removed by a vote of no confidence until December 2019.
• The odds of her dying in the time frame of this question are negligible.
• A Tory leadership election usually takes months but could be done much quicker in exceptional circumstances. (The 2016 election took just 3 weeks.) Politics;
The only realistic way that there could be a new Tory PM is if May resigns, but she is seen as a dogged and determined person who doesn't give up under any circumstances. However I suspect she might have a breaking point and would at least consider resigning if Parliament forced her to delay Brexit beyond the start of the next EU political session. We should find out how long that delay will be soon after the three critical votes coming up on 12/13/14 of this month. If Parliament forces a long delay and she doesn't resign shortly after that, then I will reduce again.
